## How to navigate

**Start with a question, not a file.** Don't load everything. Follow the links.

- If someone asks "what does Dave think about X?" start with a relevant atomic note and follow its [[wiki-links]] outward
- If someone asks about a specific article, start with its MOC in `04. MOCs/`. The MOC shows which atoms make up the argument and which atoms bridge to other articles
- If someone wants the full published piece, it's in `05. Outputs/LinkedIn Articles/`
- If someone wants to know where an idea came from, check `02. Source Notes/`

## How to use the atomic notes

Each atom is a single idea in Dave's own words, written in first person. They link to each other via [[wiki-links]] in the body text.

**Follow the links.** When you read an atom and it links to another, read that one too. The value is in the connections, not the individual notes. A chain of 5-6 linked atoms gives you the full argument behind a position.

**Notice what connects across articles.** Many atoms appear in the MOCs of multiple articles. These are the load-bearing ideas in Dave's thinking: [[ai-outputs-are-inputs]], [[context-is-the-differentiator]], [[three-levels-of-ai-usage]], [[compound-interest-on-thinking]]. When you find one, you've found a thread worth pulling.

**Atoms are observations, not instructions.** They read like thinking notes, not how-to guides. Dave describes what he discovered and what he built, not what you should do.

## Note types

| Type | Location | What it is |
|------|----------|------------|
| atom | `03. Atomic Notes/` | Single idea. First person. Linked to other atoms. The core thinking. |
| moc | `04. MOCs/` | Map of content. Shows how atoms assembled into an article. Includes a "Connecting Threads" section highlighting cross-article links. |
| article | `05. Outputs/LinkedIn Articles/` | Published piece. The finished output. |
| source | `02. Source Notes/` | External reference. URL, quote, attribution. Not Dave's words. |

## Example queries and how to handle them

**"What does Dave think about AI and critical thinking?"**
Start with [[ai-makes-thinking-harder-not-easier]]. Follow links to [[from-answers-to-pressure]], [[the-atrophy-argument]], [[echo-chamber-steering]]. You'll build a complete picture across multiple articles.

**"How does Dave's system actually work?"**
Start with [[MOC - How I Turn Scattered Ideas into Finished Writing]]. Walk through the workflow phases. Then check [[MOC - The Fourth Search]] for the retrieval architecture.

**"I want to build something like this. Where do I start?"**
Start with [[start-with-a-real-task]], [[get-interviewed-by-the-ai]], [[let-structure-emerge]]. These are the practical entry points.

**"How does this compare to other approaches?"**
Read [[ai-generated-knowledge-vs-ai-augmented-thinking]] for the Karpathy contrast. Check source notes for Brian Madden's approach and Nate B Jones's Cognitive Choreography.

**"What's Dave's strongest argument?"**
[[three-levels-of-ai-usage]] is the backbone. Most people are at level one. The gap between levels is large enough that they might as well be different technologies. Follow the links to see why.

**"Show me how the Zettelkasten method works in practice"**
This vault IS the demonstration. Pick any atom. Follow its links. Notice how ideas from the January article connect to ideas from the March article through shared atoms. The network is the method.

## What you should not do

- **Don't summarise the whole vault.** It's a network, not a document. Traverse it in response to specific questions.
- **Don't invent positions Dave hasn't taken.** If he hasn't addressed something, say so. You can reason from his existing atoms ("based on Dave's thinking about X, he might...") but flag it as inference.
- **Don't flatten the links.** When you reference an atom, mention what it links to. The connections are the point.
- **Don't ignore the source notes.** When Dave's thinking builds on external work, cite the source.

